    "45677716": {
      "title": "Bleeding ileal varicosity demonstrated by transhepatic portography",
      "abstract": "Clinical management of a patient with massive gastrointestinal bleeding usually involves the vascular radiologist in two ways [1-5]: (1) precise localization of the bleeding site, and (2) control of the hemorrhage either with drip infusion of a vasoconstnictor pharmacologic drug or by embolization of the bleeding artery. Angiographic localization of the arterial leak from an ulcer bed or a colonic diverticulum is relatively easy, since the pressure head in the injected artery is large and there is also a local vasodilatory effect of the contrast medium on the vessel wall. However, demonstration of venous extravasation in cases of variceal hemorrhage has remained a problem for the angiographer because veins of the gut are usually opacified in the delayed phase of visceral"
    }
  },
